{{Main|Mexican muralism}}

'''Mexican Renaissance''' refers to the [[Mexican muralism]] movement between 1920 and 1950.<ref name="Lopez2010" /><ref name="Beller2008">{{cite book|author=Susan Provost Beller|title=The Aftermath of the Mexican Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLAgj6eZY4oC&pg=PT107|date=1 September 2008|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=978-0-8225-7600-6|pages=107}}</ref> The phrase was first used in ''Idols behind Altars'' by [[Anita Brenner]], with [[Jean Charlot]].<ref name="Lopez2010">{{cite book|author=Rick A. Lopez|title=Crafting Mexico: Intellectuals, Artisans, and the State after the Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4rpcwrhcwcC&pg=PA108|date=19 August 2010|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-9173-9|page=108}}</ref> Charlot also discussed it in his 1963 book, ''The Mexican Mural Renaissance'':<ref name="ModottiAlbers2000">{{cite book|author1=Tina Modotti|author2=Patricia Albers|author3=Karen Cordero|title=Tina Modotti: the Mexican renaissance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d3ZOAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA16|year=2000|publisher=Jean-Michel Place editions|page=16}}</ref>

{{Quotation|There are some simplifications which have become history, and one of them is the tie, which in itself is quite true, between the Mexican Renaissance, so called, and the [[Mexican Revolution]]. By Renaissance I speak mainly of the mural period of the 1920s and of the muralists, and of course, the Revolution is the Revolution of 1910, mostly military and a rather bloody affair.|Jean Charlot<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jeancharlot.org/writings/english/1960%20MEXICAN%20RENAISSANCE.htm | title=The Mexican Mural Renaissance | publisher=Jean Charlot.com | accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>}}

